05831nam a22007575i 9780823293360DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232933607 a10.1515/97808232933602doi  a(DE-B1597)566128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0060002bisacsh1 aWolfreys, Julian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThinking Difference :bCritics in Conversation /cJulian Wolfreys. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (199 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Beginning Is Haunted: Teaching and the Uncanny -- t2 Encountering the Other in the Classroom -- t3 Symptoms of Response -- t4 Confessions of an Anacoluthon: On Writing, Technology, Pedagogy, and Politics -- t5 Difference beyond Difference -- t6 Q&A: Whims, Whim-Whams, Whimsies, and the "Responsiveble" Interview -- t7 Thinking about This ... -- t8 Resisting Resistance -- t9 Going to University with Socrates -- t10 In Praise of Devilish Hermeneutics -- t11 A-mail: Differential Imaging -- t12 The Degree Zero of Criticism -- t13 To Leave the Word to Someone Else -- tContributors -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Difference" has been a term of choice in the humanities for the last few decades, animating an extraordinary variety of work in philosophy, literary studies, religion, law, the social sciences-indeed, in virtually every area of the academy. In projects ranging from deconstructive readings of canonical texts to a radical rethinking of the sacred, "difference" has been the node around which theorists have explored questions of conflict, power, identity, meaning, and knowledge itself in postmodern culture. At this point, what difference does "difference" make? In this imaginatively conceived book, Julian Wolfreys talks to thirteen leading scholars about the place of "difference" in their own work, in their own fields, and in their teaching. How has intellectual engagement with difference-its celebration of otherness and opposition, whether in a work of art or in world politics-shaped teaching, reading, and writing in today's colleges and universities? And at a time when identity politics and cultural critique have been institutionalized by the academy, has "difference" been domesticated? Personal and revealing, these conversations come together as a kind of collective self-portrait of the humanities at one of its important junctures. Thinking Difference offers provocative reflections on what ideas and practices will drive the next generation of critical thinking. Here are original conversations on the career of a key concept with: Nicholas Royle, Derek Attridge, Peggy Kamuf, Avital Ronell, Arkady Plotnitsky, John P. Leavey, Jr., Mary Ann Caws, Jonathan Culler, Gregory L. Ulmer, J. Hillis Miller, John D. Caputo, Kevin Hart, and Werner Hamacher  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAttridge, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaputo, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaws, Mary Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuller, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamacher, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamuf, Peggy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/